The paper discusses randomized algorithms for solving linear programs and LP-type problems, which are typically studied in computer science subfields such as data structures (cs.DS), computational geometry (cs.CG), computational complexity (cs.CC), machine learning (cs.LG), and numerical analysis (cs.NA). The focus on randomized algorithms and lower bounds suggests that cs.CC and cs.DS are the most likely categories, followed by cs.CG and cs.LG, which often deal with geometric and optimization problems. Finally, cs.NA is a possible category given the mention of shortest paths and numerical methods for solving LPs.
